element.definition: May be used to represent additional information that is not part of the basic definition of the element. In order to make the use of extensions safe and manageable, there is a strict set of governance  applied to the definition and use of extensions. Though any implementer is allowed to define an extension, there is a set of requirements that SHALL be met as part of the definition of the extension.
element.comment: There can be no stigma associated with the use of extensions by any application, project, or standard - regardless of the institution or jurisdiction that uses or defines the extensions.  The use of extensions is what allows the FHIR specification to retain a core level of simplicity for everyone.

element.definition: A human-readable narrative summary that contains a reportability determination, the responsible PHA(s), and the PHA(s) that will be sent the eICR (when deemed reportable).
Each Reportability Response document should include a unique ID to allow for identification by PHA systems, EHR systems, or other interested parties.
For a given condition within a jurisdiction, the mandated timeframe in which the condition should be reported to the PHA.
A code indicating a condition associated with an RCTC trigger code in the eICR.
A code indicating whether the responsible PHA is relevant because of the patient's home address, the provider facility address, or both.

element.short: Date and time of eICR Receipt
element.definition: The date and time of eICR receipt (to assist with troubleshooting and establish the elapsed time between the EHR sending the eICR and the PHA system (or its intermediary) receiving the eICR).
At a minimum, each Reportability Response should contain the unique document ID associated with the eICR that initiated its generation.
At a minimum, each Reportability Response should contain the unique document ID associated with the eICR that initiated its generation.
The encompassing encounter ID from the eICR that generatedthe Reportability Response.
The filename of the eICR (to assist with troubleshooting in the event that the eICR cannot be parsed).
If the incoming eICR was manually generated by the provider (as opposed to automatically-generated based on the existence of a trigger code from the RCTC) then this will be present.

element.short: Initial Case Report Manual Initiation Reason*
element.definition: Reason for manual initiation of the eICR.
The status of eICR processing, including an acknowledgemen of successful processing or any known errors encountered during eICR processing.
If the incoming eICR was not processed by the PHA system (or its intermediary), will contain the reason it was not processed.
If the PHA system (or its intermediary) identifies an issue with the eICR, but is still able to process the file, this will contain those issues as a warning.
Code, codeSystem, valueSet, valueSetVersion of a code that exists within the RCTC but has been labeled as inactive.
The version of the RCTC that was expected by RCKMS. If populated, the EHR System Administrator should update to this version of the RCTC immediately.
If the version of the RCTC that was used to generate the eICR is outdated, the specific version used.
The determination of reportability generated by the PHA system (or its intermediary). Generally, this is expected to be Yes, No, or Maybe.
A reason code indicating the reason for the reportability status.
A rule that was involved in the determination of the reportability status.
The description of link which may assist “providers” or “reporters” in understanding or investigating conditions.
